{
  "texts": [
    "(2001a p. 51) For Davidson, intentions matching these descriptions are ensured by the fact that the cognitive feat of 'intending to φ' is, for any ordinary argument for 'φ', a trivial accomplishment for an adult, practically rational human.",
    "If event coding theorists are correct, then this kind of accomplishment is underwritten by cognitive mechanisms that do not harbour representations of bodily movements abstracted from their wider consequences.",
    "In this case, intending to move in just the way required to tie one's shoelaces always requires internal representations of the shoelaces and their getting tied.",
    "But having an intention with this or any other kind of content doesn't entail action; it is only a sufficient cause for it in the right circumstances.",
    "And when circumstances are right, the intention fixes one end of an action's causal profile.What about the other end?"
  ]
}